<DESCRIPT>  DEATH; OBITUARY; NAME; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  BOLZ, Sanford Hegleman, 76, a lawyer who as Washington counsel for the
American Jewish Congress was active in civil rights cases in the 1950s; Monday
of cancer in Washington. After graduating from Cornell University Law School
in 1938, Mr. Bolz was a research assistant with the New York State Law
Revision Commission and an associate with a Manhattan law firm before joining
the National Labor Relations Board in 1941.;    BOWEN, Joe, 56, who supervised
the buying, screening and editing of theatrical feature films for CBS
Entertainment; Sunday of a heart attack at his home in Los Angeles. Mr.
Bowen's career with CBS started in New York City at WCBS-TV, where he began
work as a program assistant in 1960. He was promoted to film-continuity editor
and then held a variety of positions with the network, including supervisor of
feature-film productions, program executive for late-night movies and
associate director of prime-time features. In 1979, he moved to Los Angeles,
where he became director of feature films and late-night program director.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DEATHS ELSEWHERE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Obituaries  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     FINK, Joseph, 76, a retired deputy inspector on the New York City Police
Department who in the 1960s gained a national reputation for his sensitive
handling of hippies in the East Village; Sunday of cancer at Universal Medical
Center in Pompano Beach, Fla. A former professor of police science, Mr. Fink
was the co-author of "The Community and the Police: Conflict or Cooperation,"
a book on his experiences in community relations. He was a past president of
the Shomrim Society, an organization of Jewish police officers.;    GOODY,
Sam, 87, an entrepreneur who made millions selling records and tapes from a
nationwide chain of stores bearing his name; Thursday in a New York hospital.
Mr. Goody, born Samuel Gutowitz and nicknamed "Goody" as a child, started out
as a businessman selling toys and novelties. In 1938, after a customer asked
if he had any records, he began selling 10-inch, 78 rpm records. His business
took off after World War II, when long-playing 12-inch records became
popular.;    JEROME, Judson, 64, a writer and teacher who published more than
a dozen books of fiction, non-fiction and poetry; Monday of cancer in Yellow
Springs, Ohio. Mr. Jerome taught courses in writing at Antioch College in the
west central Ohio community for 20 years. He also worked for 30 years as a
poetry columnist at Writer's Digest magazine and was editor of the annual
Poets' Market.;    MICHENER, Roland, former governor-general who was Canada's
head of state during its centennial year in 1967; Tuesday in Ottawa. Mr.
Michener was appointed to the largely ceremonial post in 1967 and served until
1974. He was Canada's top host in 1967 to more than 50 royal visitors and
heads of state from other lands. As the queen's representative in Canada, the
governor-general signs all legislation before it becomes law.;    ROOSEVELT,
Cornelius Van Schaak, 75, former Central Intelligence Agency official, who
headed an agency unit designed to foil electronic eavesdropping; Aug. 2 in his
Washington home of a heart attack. Mr. Roosevelt, a grandson of President
Theodore Roosevelt, was also an engineer and business executive who worked in
China, an art collector and amateur archaeologist. A native of New York, he
attended Harvard University and graduated from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. He joined the CIA in Washington in 1952.;    He became chief of
the technical services division of the agency and later chairman of the
technical surveillance countermeasures committee, a panel whose role was to
thwart electronic eavesdropping. He retired from the CIA in 1973.  </TEXT>
